Sounds like you're doing fine anon, if you start learning theory it will probably go pretty fast after going through the trouble of learning bossa nova by ear. You'll be going "ohh so that's what it was".
I don't think being able to read is extremely important, it is a skill that will help you more the better you are at it, but i think the most important thing is that you learn to identify what you're hearing. So i suggest you practice hearing intervals, as in being able to hear C and A and saying "this is a major 6th", and chord functions, which means what scale degree is the root of a chord on.

Like say you have the major scale that goes C D E F G A B C, for the chords to not sound out of place (or at least in a controlled way), each of them has to be of a type that puts the rest of the notes inside the scale as well (bar many exceptions), that's why C is major, and D is minor, and E is minor, etc. If you were in the key of C and tried to play A major, it contains a C# and you'd either be implying another key or sounding like you're on your way to another more stable chord.
Eventually, you can extend this reasoning to having all the notes in the scale in one chord, with a certain root, and that's what some people call modes, but i think you should just treat them as chords. You don't have to play 7 note chords, it just occasionally helps to think that way if you're playing a melody that tries to imply a specific harmony.
